***Documentation of My AI Data Analysis Project***

Introduction:
In this project I analyzed a dataset called students_ai_usage.csv. The assigments purpose was to analzye the data, understand how students use artificial intelligence tools and whether using AI seems connected to changes in grades, study habits and screen time. 
I also used some more advanced data analysis methods like PCA, ICA, FFT, wavelets, and filtering.

While writing this code I divided the notebook into clear parts for better organization. Each section has a different purpose like loading the data, cleaning it, analyzing it, visualizing it or applying transforms.

***Description of the Data:***

The dataset contains information about students and their AI usage. Some of the columns are:
		age
		education_level
		study_hours_per_day
		uses_ai
		ai_tools_used
		purpose_of_ai
		grades_before_ai
		grades_after_ai
		daily_screen_time_hours

This dataset mixes both numerical data and categorical data. For example, grades and study hours are numerical meaning numbers, while education level and AI tool used are categorical meaning words.
I also created two extra variables:
		grade_improvement = grades_after_ai - grades_before_ai
		uses_ai_binary = converting Yes/No into 1/0

These new columns made it easier to compare students and calculate graphs.

***Data Inspection and Cleaning:***

The first step in my code was loading the dataset and inspecting it. I checked:
		the first 5 rows
		dataset shape
		column names
		dataset info
		missing values

This helped me understand what I was working with before working with it.
After that I cleaned the data by removing extra spaces from the column names and from text columns meaning the empty data values.

***Descriptive Analysis:***

After cleaning the data, I explored it with descriptive statistics. I used .describe() for the numeric columns and .value_counts() for the categorical columns. This helped me see the overall patterns in the dataset, like averages, spreads, and how often each category appeared.

Then I created visualizations such as:
		bar charts for AI usage and education level (Bar charts are graphs that use rectangular shapes to show how often a value appears.)
		histogram of grade improvement (A graph that shows how often different number ranges appear)
		scatter plots showing relationships between:
		study hours and grades after AI
		screen time and grade improvement
		grades before AI and grades after AI (Scatter Plot is a graph to see the relationship for two variables using dots.)

These graphs made the dataset easier to understand. Instead of only reading numbers I could see the patterns.

***Comparing Different Groups:***

One of the most important parts of my analysis was comparing groups. I compared:
		AI users vs non-users
		different AI tools
		different purposes of AI use
		school students vs college students

For example:
I calculated the average study time, grades, screen time and grade improvement for AI users and non-users. I also checked which AI tools were linked to higher average grade improvement and whether using AI for homework, research or coding made any difference.

***Correlation Analysis:***

Next I used a correlation matrix and a heatmap to measure how close the numerical variables were related to each other. The correlation helps show patterns if there is a relationship or not.
For example this analysis can help show whether grade improvement is related to study hours, screen time or AI use. The heatmap was useful because it made the correlations easier to read with color and numbers together.
- A Heatmap is a graph that uses colors to show the strength of values or their relationships in data.
- A correlation matrix is a table that shows how strongly some variables are related to each other.

***Preprocessing for PCA and ICA:***

- PCA is a method that reduces data into the most important values skipping the repeating ones.
- ICA is a method that separates hidden independent patterns in the data.

Before using PCA and ICA I needed to preprocess the dataset properly. Since the dataset has both numeric and categorical columns, I used:
		SimpleImputer to fill missing values with values that hold no value
		StandardScaler to scale numeric features into less complex versions
		OneHotEncoder to convert categorical features into machine-readable form meaning converting yes/no to 0/1.
		ColumnTransformer and Pipeline to organize these steps

This preprocessing part is important because advanced methods like PCA and ICA need the data in a clean numerical format or else it wouldnt be accurate.


****PCA Analysis:***

I used Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to reduce the dataset into 2 main components. PCA helps generate the most important values in the data with fewer dimensions.

In my project, PCA allowed me to:
		project the dataset into 2D
		visualize students in a simpler way
		measure explained variance
		find which original features contributed most strongly to the principal components

I also printed the top feature loadings for PC1 and PC2. This helped me understand which variables had the biggest influence inside the dataset in the basic representation.


***ICA Analysis:***

I also used Independent Component Analysis (ICA). Unlike PCA which focuses on variance ICA tries to separate hidden independent patterns in the data.
In this project ICA was another way to visualize the structure of the dataset and compare it with PCA. Even if the dataset was not a perfect for ICA calculation it still helped demonstrate a different kind of transform and showed how independent patterns might appear in student data.


***Signal Processing Demonstrations:***

One of the most creative parts of my project was turning the grade_improvement column into a simple one-dimensional signal meaning reading all the values as 1 line. I clearly noted in the code that this is only a demonstration because the student index is not a true time axis. 


***Sonification:***

I converted the signal I created into audio. This means I turned the data into sound so it could be explored in a different way. This was interesting because it showed that data does not always need to be seen as a graph it can also be converted to audio.

***FFT:***

- Fast Fourier Transform is a method that breaks a signal into its different frequencies to show hidden patterns.
I used the Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) to study the frequency content of the signal. This showed whether there were repeating patterns or dominant frequencies in the sequence.


***Spectrogram:***

- A spectrogram is a graph that is used to show how the frequencies in a signal change over time if they change.
I created a spectrogram to show how the frequency changed across the signal. 


***Wavelets:***

- Wavelets are a method used to detect patterns in a signal at different scales and positions.
I applied a wavelet transform to look at localized patterns meaning patterns that appear at certain values at different scales. Wavelets are useful because they can capture both position and scale at the same time unlike FFT which focuses on frequency only.


***Filters:***

I used low-pass and high-pass Butterworth filters.
		The low-pass filter smoothed the signal. (The low pass filter removes the fast frequencies.)
		The high-pass filter highlighted faster changes. (The high pass filter removes the slow frequencies.)

This taught me how filters can isolate different kinds of patterns.

***Compressed Sensing Style Demonstration:***

Finally I created a simple compressed sensing style demo by randomly sampling only part of the signal meaning I kept some random data points and reconstructing the rest with interpolation this means I estimated the missing values between the points I had.

